node.text: Two months ago after our @wegavewhat Passover initiative, we planned an interview with an inspiring Holocaust survivor to educate and raise awareness. This interview is timely to say the least, and I apologize for my emotions during it. Please meet Hedy Bohm, a 93 year old Holocaust survivor who’s family was sent to Auschwitz concentration camp in 1944. I URGE you to listen to her story, every minute of it. After spending 3 days in cattle cars (which she described as 90 Jews pressed together like sardines with no food and one bucket), she arrived at Auschwitz and within 1 minute was separated from both her parents. She later found out they were sent directly into gas chambers and killed. That is the just the beginning of her story, please watch and hear from her yourself. 6 million Jews were killed in the Holocaust. I condemn hate and violence of any kind, against any religion, against any people. It is deeply upsetting to see the division in our world today, and I pray for peace. [the text was automatically generated so there may be some errors but I wanted you to be able to read her words too] Thank you for taking the time.

node.text: Holy moly I can not believe it’s been a full year since we set out on a mission to give back - past the pandemic. Alex, our tiny but mighty team, and YOU our powerful community have made such a difference in so many peoples lives. This has by far been the most fulfilling work of my career, and has given me a newfound purpose. Over the past year we have raised hundreds of thousands of dollars that have directly supported incredible organizations, helped save dozens of small businesses, raised awareness for important issues with calls to action, collected supplies for multiple disaster reliefs, donated over one million miles to directly unite refugee families, helped feed thousands of families on holidays and donated toys, school, and baby supplies to children in need, launched two pop-ups for small businesses, and made so many new friends along the way. Whether it’s our voice, our time, our compassion, our resources, or our support; WE ALL HAVE SOMETHING TO GIVE. And we’re just getting started. 🥺☺️🤍

There’s no question that this year has put us all to the test in ways we never could have imagined.. our world has faced more hardships and loss in the past 6 plus months than it has in the past 6 years. The need for reflection and introspection has been forced upon us, and it’s hard to even begin to describe how much this year has changed so many, including myself. We’ve been forced to have uncomfortable conversations, deal with emotions and mental health that ran so deep and were so serious, and ground ourselves through it all with gratitude for the things we do have. The little things that have become precious, holding onto them so tightly. We’ve learned that we all have something to give, and I personally feel this massive responsibility to use this very platform in new ways: to help others, to spread positive messages, to educate, to influence for good, to facilitate change through our community, to amplify the voices of others, and to share more purposefully and mission driven, more transparently and authentically. This is my year in review, it’s flawed and imperfect, I’ve made mistakes along the way and own the need to do better, always. I feel extremely grateful every single day for the opportunity to grow. I know so many of you are tired and just want 2020 to be over, I get it and always want to be here for you. It helps me to remember strength grows in the moments when you think you can’t go on, but continue anyway. You are brave and YOU CAN, so let’s move forward into a new year together. Thank you to every health professional & essential worker for being the real heroes of 2020. And thank you guys from the bottom of my heart for following and for being my rock. 
❤️

Thank you to @revolve & @raissagerona for giving me this opportunity to speak freely, vulnerably, and honestly. It’s certainly not easy, but I’m not afraid to speak about some of the hard challenges I have faced publicly (in fact I welcome it on my own terms), and I hope my followers (and non followers) will take the time to listen to what I have to say. I’ve truly worked so hard to build my brand authentically for nearly the past decade - while growing up in front of the camera at my own hand. Having shared so much of myself with so many people has not come without its challenges. I appreciate all my followers more than you know, and I hope this provides a little more insight. I have some very exciting news coming your way tomorrow, in our mission to further support incredible small businesses. I cannot wait to share with you guys and take you onward and upward to the next chapter!

node.text: I want to speak to you guys from the heart.. when the pandemic hit I had this newfound sense of responsibility to give back more than ever before. I wanted to take immediate action, and knew the quickest way to help would be to lend my platform to those who needed it. I opened myself up to hear from small businesses around the world, and shared so many of them with my community. When I realized the massive impact this had, I knew I needed to extend this and create a place where more businesses and organizations could be amplified. As I launched new product, I made sure each and every collection was tied to a give back initiative, whether it was donating thousands of masks to frontline health heroes, or tens of thousands of dollars to food pantry organizations.. TOGETHER, we have been able to help so many people, so quickly, partnering with the most beautiful souls along the way. We created @wegavewhat as a way to continue this good work past the pandemic. We are in the process of seeking our official 501(c)(3) status, and have so many amazing things planned to help so many more people. Our website officially launches today - on it you can visit our volunteer opportunities, small business directory, and learn about the many great charities we have gotten to know over the past few months. Our work is just beginning - and whether it’s our voice, our compassion, our support, or our resources - WE ALL HAVE SOMETHING TO GIVE.
